{"parentUuid":"6435d9ee-55f0-4987-b658-e7ec20fe5a2a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"ab2d46b6d40ad5f45","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccqb9ics1VkSSnYoN4orf","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I've completed the removed-behavior audit of the metric-quotas data path. I read the full diff plus the new (untracked) files that the diff wires in (`quotas_repo.py`, `quota_service.py`, `routes/quotas.py`, the migration), and traced each deleted/replaced line to where its invariant is re-established.\n\n## Summary: the audited invariants are re-established\n\nFor each replaced line I confirmed the guard survives:\n\n- **errors.py** — `code = _STATUS_TO_CODE.get(...)` → `getattr(exc, \"app_code\", None) or _STATUS_TO_CODE.get(...)`. Envelope shape unchanged; the `headers=` propagation line (Retry-After) was already present and is untouched. The 429 `rate_limited` vs `quota_exceeded` distinction is real (test AC14 confirms).\n- **api_key.py / api_keys_repo.py** — `AuthenticatedPrincipal` gains `scope` with a fail-closed default (`\"ingest\"`); `verify_api_key` always populates it from the record; migration 0003 backfills `scope='ingest'` NOT NULL + CHECK. No privilege default-open.\n- **events_service.py** — the change is purely additive inside `if inserted is not None:`. Idempotent-replay path (line 137-152) unchanged → replays still skip both the quota check and the rollup increment (test AC11). Mass-assignment protection (server sets `api_key_id`/`window_start`) intact. Rollback-on-reject is genuine: `QuotaExceededError` propagates out of `scoped_transaction`'s `session.begin()`, which rolls back (session.py line 59), so no partial event/rollup write (test AC9/AC10).\n- **rollup atomicity / strict enforcement** — the `FOR UPDATE` on the quota row serializes concurrent same-tenant events; the separate post-lock `usage_rollup` read gets a fresh READ COMMITTED snapshot. The check-then-increment is inside one lock-held transaction. No over-admit path found.\n- **middleware.py** — only adds `PUT` to CORS methods (additive).\n\n## Candidate findings (both low-confidence / PLAUSIBLE)\n\n**1. src/api/errors.py:88 — falsy `app_code` silently falls back to the status map**\n- Summary: `getattr(exc, \"app_code\", None) or _STATUS_TO_CODE.get(...)` treats an empty-string `app_code` as absent.\n- Failure scenario: a future `AppError(status_code=429, app_code=\"\", ...)` (or any falsy code) would emit `code:\"rate_limited\"` instead of its intended distinct code, collapsing the very distinction this change exists to make. Current callers always pass a non-empty literal, so not triggerable today — defensive only.\n\n**2. src/repositories/quotas_repo.py:116-149 — strict enforcement is silently coupled to READ COMMITTED isolation**\n- Summary: the two-statement \"lock quota row, then re-read rollup\" correctness argument holds only under READ COMMITTED (each statement gets a fresh snapshot); the code neither sets nor asserts the isolation level.\n- Failure scenario: if the engine in `db/session.py` were ever configured with `isolation_level=\"REPEATABLE READ\"`, a queued waiter's post-lock `usage_rollup` read would use the transaction's original snapshot, reading a stale `total_quantity` and admitting events past the cap (or raising a serialization 500) — the exact over-admit the module docstring claims to prevent. The engine currently uses the driver default (RC), so this is a latent coupling, not a live bug.\n\nNo higher-confidence correctness defect from removed or replaced behavior was found — the quota-enforcement rewrite preserves the idempotent-replay path, rollup-increment atomicity, mass-assignment protection, error-envelope shape, and the `quota.rejected` logging contract."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10303,"cache_read_input_tokens":49730,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":10303,"ephemeral_1